Introduction¶

For this tutorial we will be exploring whether Covid-19 had any affect to the number of crimes or types of crimes in Los Angeles.

Getting the Data¶

For this tutorial the following tools are needed. The ones essential to most data analysis include pandas, numpy, matplotlib, and scikit-learn

Processing the Data¶

One of the first things to do is to see if our dataframe contains any missing or duplicated data in its entries. Of course if you won't be using an attribute in your dataframe that has missing values then there's no need to do anything. With our crime dataframe, we want to first check if there are duplicates so we need to use something that can be unique to each crime. It just so happens that each crime has a unique 'DR_NO' so we can count how many of these unique 'DR_NO' values are in the dataframe and compare it to the number of entries in the dataframe.

In [5]:
num_ids = crimes_df['DR_NO'].unique().size
print(f'duplicate entries: {crimes_df.index.size - num_ids}')

crimes_df.drop_duplicates(['DR_NO'], inplace = True)
print(f'duplicate entries after removal: {crimes_df.index.size - num_ids}')

duplicate entries: 227308
duplicate entries after removal: 0

After checking for duplicates, now we want to check if there are any missing values in our columns of interest. It's very important to check for missing values because they can completely change how we view the data. Sometimes the values missing could have contributed a lot to what the trend of the data actually is. So make sure you know whether your data has missing values so you can be sure whether your analysis is completely accurate or could be unreliable.

In [6]:

In this case we were lucky and there happens to be no missing values in our columns of interest. So we can proceed to the next step.

The dataframe makes the 'DATE OCC' a String so we will use the pandas to_datetime function to convert the String into a date variable. The added parameter errors='coerce' changes any value that can't be converted to a date variable to be NaT (not a time). We then use the method dropna based on the 'DATE OCC' attribute to remove these NaT from our dataframe

In [7]:
crimes_df['DATE OCC'] = pd.to_datetime(crimes_df['DATE OCC'], errors = 'coerce')
crimes_df.dropna(subset = ['DATE OCC'], inplace = True)

The cvoid cases data from the New York Times only records the cumulative number of covid cases. So if we want to view the number of cases that occur each day we can subtract the cumulative number of covid cases from the day before with the one today.

In [13]:
covid_df.rename(columns = {'cases': 'cumulative cases', 'deaths': 'cumulative deaths'}, inplace = True)

for i in range(1, len(covid_df)):
    covid_df.loc[i, 'cases'] = covid_df['cumulative cases'][i] - covid_df['cumulative cases'][i - 1]

# the loop doesn't take into account the very first entry, but we know that the cumulative covid cases should be the same as the
# first recorded day of covid cases
covid_df.loc[0, 'cases'] = covid_df['cumulative cases'][0]

def get_perc_crimes(df, crime_lst):
    crime_num = []
    
    for crime in crime_lst:
        crime_num.append((crime, (df[df['Crm Cd Desc'] == crime].index.size) / df.index.size))
    
    return crime_num

def get_crime_hours(df):
    hours = []
    
    for i in range(len(df)):
        hours.append(df['TIME OCC'][i].hour)
    
    return hours

from scipy.optimize import curve_fit

def sigmoid(x, a, b): y = 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-b*(x-a))) return y

popt, pcov = curve_fit(sigmoid, years, vehicle_crime_percent, method='dogbox', bounds=(0, 1))

yd = sigmoid(years, *popt) plt.scatter(years, vehicle_crime_percent) plt.plot(years, yd) plt.legend(loc='best') plt.show()

In [38]:
def get_num_stolen_vehicles(df, year, mnth):
    dict = {}
    dict['year'] = year
    dict['month'] = mnth
    dict['stolen vehicles'] = df[(df['year'] == year) & (df['month'] == mnth)].index.size
    
    if year >= 2021:
        dict['during covid'] = 'Y'
    elif year == 2020 & mnth >= 3:
        dict['during covid'] = 'Y'
    else:
        dict['during covid'] = 'N'
        
    return dict
